### ðŸŸ¢ Stage 1: Basics of BFS and DFS on Graphs

|---|---|---|

---

### ðŸŸ¡ Stage 2: Unweighted Graphs â€“ Use BFS for Shortest Path

In unweighted graphs, the shortest path is the fewest number of steps. Use BFS here.

|   |   |   |
|---|---|---|
|#|Problem|Concept|
|5|752. Open the Lock|BFS with visited set|
|6|127. Word Ladder|BFS + string transformation|

|8|279. Perfect Squares|BFS on numbers|

âœ… Goal: Master BFS to find shortest path in unweighted problems (grids, strings, queues).

---

### ðŸ”µ Stage 3: Weighted Graphs â€“ Dijkstraâ€™s Algorithm

If weights are involved, use Dijkstraâ€™s Algorithm (greedy + priority queue)

|   |   |   |
|---|---|---|
|#|Problem|Concept|
|9|743. Network Delay Time|Basic Dijkstra|

âœ… Goal: Understand and implement Dijkstra using a priority queue

### ðŸ”´ Stage 4: Advanced Algorithms (Optional)

If you master above, then try:

- Bellman-Ford (for negative weights)  
- Floyd-Warshall (all-pairs shortest path)
